# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hierarchical-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Frequentist statistics may yield conclusions seemingly incompatible with those offered by Bayesian statistics due to the Bayesian treatment of the parameters as random variables and its use of subjective information in establishing assumptions on these parameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] As the approaches answer different questions the formal results are not technically contradictory but the two approaches disagree over which answer is relevant to particular applications.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Bayesians argue that relevant information regarding decision-making and updating beliefs cannot be ignored and that hierarchical modeling has the potential to overrule classical methods in applications where respondents give multiple observational data.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Moreover, the model has proven to be robust, with the posterior distribution less sensitive to the more flexible hierarchical priors.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Hierarchical modeling, as its name implies, retains nested data structure, and is used when information is available at several different levels of observational units.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] For example, in epidemiological modeling to describe infection trajectories for multiple countries, observational units are countries, and each country has its own time-based profile of daily infected cases.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] In decline curve analysis to describe oil or gas production decline curve for multiple wells, observational units are oil or gas wells in a reservoir region, and each well has each own time-based profile of oil or gas production rates (usually, barrels per month).
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Hierarchical modeling is used to devise computation based strategies for multiparameter problems.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Statistical methods and models commonly involve multiple parameters that can be regarded as related or connected in such a way that the problem implies a dependence of the joint probability model for these parameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Individual degrees of belief, expressed in the form of probabilities, come with uncertainty.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Amidst this is the change of the degrees of belief over time.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Smith, "The actuality of the learning process consists in the evolution of individual and subjective beliefs about the reality." These subjective probabilities are more directly involved in the mind rather than the physical probabilities.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Hence, it is with this need of updating beliefs that Bayesians have formulated an alternative statistical model which takes into account the prior occurrence of a particular event.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The assumed occurrence of a real-world event will typically modify preferences between certain options.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] This is done by modifying the degrees of belief attached, by an individual, to the events defining the options.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] In order to make updated probability statements about $\theta _{j}$ , given the occurrence of event *y*, we must begin with a model providing a joint probability distribution for $\theta _{j}$ and *y*.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] This equation, showing the relationship between the conditional probability and the individual events, is known as Bayes' theorem.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] This simple expression encapsulates the technical core of Bayesian inference which aims to deconstruct the probability, $P(\theta \mid y)$ , relative to solvable subsets of its supportive evidence.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The usual starting point of a statistical analysis is the assumption that the *n* values $y_{1},y_{2},\ldots ,y_{n}$ are exchangeable.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] If no information – other than data *y* – is available to distinguish any of the $\theta _{j}$ 's from any others, and no ordering or grouping of the parameters can be made, one must assume symmetry of prior distribution parameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] This symmetry is represented probabilistically by exchangeability.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Generally, it is useful and appropriate to model data from an exchangeable distribution as independently and identically distributed, given some unknown parameter vector $\theta$ , with distribution $P(\theta )$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] For a fixed number *n*, the set $y_{1},y_{2},\ldots ,y_{n}$ is exchangeable if the joint probability $P(y_{1},y_{2},\ldots ,y_{n})$ is invariant under permutations of the indices.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The following is an exchangeable, but not independent and identical (iid), example: Consider an urn with a red ball and a blue ball inside, with probability ${\frac {1}{2}}$ of drawing either.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Balls are drawn without replacement, i.e. after one ball is drawn from the n balls, there will be $n-1$ remaining balls left for the next draw.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] But the probability of selecting a red ball on the second draw given that the red ball has already been selected in the first is 0.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] If $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ are independent and identically distributed, then they are exchangeable, but the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Infinite exchangeability is the property that every finite subset of an infinite sequence $y_{1}$ , $y_{2},\ldots$ is exchangeable.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Suppose a random variable *Y* follows a normal distribution with parameter $\theta$ as the mean and 1 as the variance, that is $Y\mid \theta \sim N(\theta ,1)$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The tilde relation $\sim$ can be read as "has the distribution of" or "is distributed as".
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Suppose also that the parameter $\theta$ has a distribution given by a normal distribution with mean $\mu$ and variance 1, i.e. $\theta \mid \mu \sim N(\mu ,1)$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Furthermore, $\mu$ follows another distribution given, for example, by the standard normal distribution, ${\text{N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The parameter $\mu$ is called the hyperparameter, while its distribution given by ${\text{N}}(0,1)$ is an example of a hyperprior distribution.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The notation of the distribution of *Y* changes as another parameter is added, i.e. $Y\mid \theta ,\mu \sim N(\theta ,1)$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] If there is another stage, say, $\mu$ following another normal distribution with a mean of $\beta$ and a variance of $\epsilon$ , then $\mu \sim N(\beta ,\epsilon )$ , ${\mbox{ }}$ $\beta$ and $\epsilon$ can also be called hyperparameters with hyperprior distributions.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Let $y_{j}$ be an observation and $\theta _{j}$ a parameter governing the data generating process for $y_{j}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Assume further that the parameters $\theta _{1},\theta _{2},\ldots ,\theta _{j}$ are generated exchangeably from a common population, with distribution governed by a hyperparameter $\phi$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The likelihood, as seen in stage I is $P(y_{j}\mid \theta _{j},\phi )$ , with $P(\theta _{j},\phi )$ as its prior distribution.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Note that the likelihood depends on $\phi$ only through $\theta _{j}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] With $\phi$ as its hyperparameter with hyperprior distribution, $P(\phi )$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] As an example, a teacher wants to estimate how well a student did on the SAT.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The teacher uses the current grade point average (GPA) of the student for an estimate.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Their current GPA, denoted by Y , has a likelihood given by some probability function with parameter $\theta$ , i.e. $Y\mid \theta \sim P(Y\mid \theta )$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] This parameter $\theta$ is the SAT score of the student.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The SAT score is viewed as a sample coming from a common population distribution indexed by another parameter $\phi$ , which is the high school grade of the student (freshman, sophomore, junior or senior).
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] That is, $\theta \mid \phi \sim P(\theta \mid \phi )$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Moreover, the hyperparameter $\phi$ follows its own distribution given by $P(\phi )$ , a hyperprior.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] All information in the problem will be used to solve for the posterior distribution.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Instead of solving only using the prior distribution and the likelihood function, using hyperpriors allows a more nuanced distinction of relationships between given variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Here, $y_{ij}$ denotes the continuous response of the i -th subject at the time point $t_{ij}$ , and $x_{ib}$ is the b -th covariate of the i -th subject.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Parameters involved in the model are written in Greek letters.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The variable $f(t;\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{K})$ is a known function parameterized by the K -dimensional vector $(\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{K})$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Typically, f is a `nonlinear' function and describes the temporal trajectory of individuals.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] In the model, $\epsilon _{ij}$ and $\eta _{li}$ describe within-individual variability and between-individual variability, respectively.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] If the prior is not considered, the relationship reduces to a frequentist nonlinear mixed-effect model.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The panel on the right displays Bayesian research cycle using Bayesian nonlinear mixed-effects model.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] A research cycle using the Bayesian nonlinear mixed-effects model comprises two steps: (a) standard research cycle and (b) Bayesian-specific workflow.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] A standard research cycle involves 1) literature review, 2) defining a problem and 3) specifying the research question and hypothesis.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Bayesian-specific workflow stratifies this approach to include three sub-steps: (b)–(i) formalizing prior distributions based on background knowledge and prior elicitation; (b)–(ii) determining the likelihood function based on a nonlinear function f ; and (b)–(iii) making a posterior inference.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] The resulting posterior inference can be used to start a new research cycle.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] Hierarchical Bayesian frameworks have been applied for modeling, e.g., Reinforcement learning and decision-making tasks, antigen mutation effects on the immune system, and ecological processes affecting species distribution, to mention a few.
[src:hierarchical-models/bayesian-hierarchical-modeling] PyMC is a flexible open source Python package supporting such modeling.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] It arose sequentially in two main published papers.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The earlier version of the estimator was developed in 1956, when Charles Stein reached a relatively shocking conclusion that while the then-usual estimate of the mean, the sample mean, is admissible when $m\leq 2$ , it is inadmissible when $m\geq 3$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Stein proposed a possible improvement to the estimator that shrinks the sample mean ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ towards a more central mean vector ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ (which can be chosen a priori or commonly as the "average of averages" of the sample means, given all samples share the same size).
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This observation is commonly referred to as Stein's example or paradox.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] In 1961, Willard James and Charles Stein simplified the original process.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] It can be shown that the James–Stein estimator dominates the "ordinary" least squares approach in the sense that the James–Stein estimator has a lower mean squared error than the "ordinary" least squares estimator for all ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This is possible because the James–Stein estimator is biased, so that the Gauss–Markov theorem does not apply.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Similar to the Hodges' estimator, the James-Stein estimator is superefficient and non-regular at ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Let ${\mathbf {Y} }\sim N_{m}({\boldsymbol {\theta }},\sigma ^{2}I),\,$ where the vector ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ is the unknown mean of ${\mathbf {Y} }$ , which is m -variate normally distributed and with known covariance matrix $\sigma ^{2}I$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] We are interested in obtaining an estimate, ${\widehat {\boldsymbol {\theta }}}$ , of ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ , based on a single observation, ${\mathbf {y} }$ , of ${\mathbf {Y} }$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] In real-world application, this is a common situation in which a set of parameters is sampled, and the samples are corrupted by independent Gaussian noise.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Since this noise has mean of zero, it may be reasonable to use the samples themselves as an estimate of the parameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This approach is the least squares estimator, which is ${\widehat {\boldsymbol {\theta }}}_{LS}={\mathbf {Y} }$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The paradoxical result, that there is a (possibly) better and never any worse estimate of ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ in mean squared error as compared to the sample mean, became known as Stein's example.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] James and Stein showed that the above estimator dominates ${\widehat {\boldsymbol {\theta }}}_{LS}$ for any $m\geq 3$ , meaning that the James–Stein estimator has a lower mean squared error (MSE) than the maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] By definition, this makes the least squares estimator inadmissible when $m\geq 3$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Notice that if $(m-2)\sigma ^{2}<\|{\mathbf {Y} }\|^{2}$ then this estimator simply takes the natural estimator $\mathbf {Y}$ and shrinks it towards the origin **0**.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] In fact this is not the only direction of shrinkage that works.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Let ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ be an arbitrary fixed vector of dimension m .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The James–Stein estimator dominates the usual estimator for any ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] A natural question to ask is whether the improvement over the usual estimator is independent of the choice of ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The improvement is small if $\|{{\boldsymbol {\theta }}-{\boldsymbol {\nu }}}\|$ is large.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Thus to get a very great improvement some knowledge of the location of ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ is necessary.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Of course this is the quantity we are trying to estimate so we don't have this knowledge a priori.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] But we may have some guess as to what the mean vector is.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This can be considered a disadvantage of the estimator: the choice is not objective as it may depend on the beliefs of the researcher.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Nonetheless, James and Stein's result is that *any* finite guess ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ improves the expected MSE over the maximum-likelihood estimator, which is tantamount to using an infinite ${\boldsymbol {\nu }}$ , surely a poor guess.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Seeing the James–Stein estimator as an empirical Bayes method gives some intuition to this result: One assumes that ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ itself is a random variable with prior distribution $\sim N(0,A)$ , where A is estimated from the data itself.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Estimating A only gives an advantage compared to the maximum-likelihood estimator when the dimension m is large enough; hence it does not work for $m\leq 2$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The James–Stein estimator is a member of a class of Bayesian estimators that dominate the maximum-likelihood estimator.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] A quirky example would be estimating the speed of light, tea consumption in Taiwan, and hog weight in Montana, all together.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The James–Stein estimator always improves upon the *total* MSE, i.e., the sum of the expected squared errors of each component.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Therefore, the total MSE in measuring light speed, tea consumption, and hog weight would improve by using the James–Stein estimator.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] However, any particular component (such as the speed of light) would improve for some parameter values, and deteriorate for others.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Thus, although the James–Stein estimator dominates the LS estimator when three or more parameters are estimated, any single component does not dominate the respective component of the LS estimator.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The conclusion from this hypothetical example is that measurements should be combined if one is interested in minimizing their total MSE.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] For example, in a telecommunication setting, it is reasonable to combine channel tap measurements in a channel estimation scenario, as the goal is to minimize the total channel estimation error.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The James–Stein estimator has also found use in fundamental quantum theory, where the estimator has been used to improve the theoretical bounds of the entropic uncertainty principle for more than three measurements.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] An intuitive derivation and interpretation is given by the Galtonian perspective.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] Under this interpretation, we aim to predict the population means using the imperfectly measured sample means.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The equation of the OLS estimator in a hypothetical regression of the population means on the sample means gives an estimator of the form of either the James–Stein estimator (when we force the OLS intercept to equal 0) or of the Efron-Morris estimator (when we allow the intercept to vary).
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This can be remedied by replacing this multiplier by zero when it is negative.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This estimator has a smaller risk than the basic James–Stein estimator for $m\geq 4$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] It follows that the basic James–Stein estimator is itself inadmissible.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] It turns out, however, that the positive-part estimator is also inadmissible.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This follows from a more general result which requires admissible estimators to be smooth.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] where the variance coefficient $\sigma ^{2}$ is known and we wish to estimate the unknown (mean response) coefficient ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}=\mathbb {E} \mathbf {Y}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] where $\mathbf {X} =[\mathbf {v} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {v} _{m}]$ is a matrix with m columns.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] As in the previous section, we can use the *positive-part James-Stein shrinkage operator* to obtain a shrinkage estimator of ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] is a (positive-part) James-Stein estimator of ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ with the useful property that it performs both shrinkage and model selection simultaneously.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] In other words, some (or all) of the $\theta _{i}$ could be estimated as exactly zero, which is equivalent to the selection of a suitable linear regression model.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] The James–Stein estimator may seem at first sight to be a result of some peculiarity of the problem setting.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] In fact, the estimator exemplifies a very wide-ranging effect; namely, the fact that the "ordinary" or least squares estimator is often inadmissible for simultaneous estimation of several parameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/james-stein-estimator] This effect has been called Stein's phenomenon, and has been demonstrated for several different problem settings, some of which are briefly outlined below.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models are particularly appropriate for research designs where data for participants are organized at more than one level (i.e., nested data).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The units of analysis are usually individuals (at a lower level) who are nested within contextual/aggregate units (at a higher level).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] While the lowest level of data in multilevel models is usually an individual, repeated measurements of individuals may also be examined.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] As such, multilevel models provide an alternative type of analysis for univariate or multivariate analysis of repeated measures.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Individual differences in growth curves may be examined.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Furthermore, multilevel models can be used as an alternative to ANCOVA, where scores on the dependent variable are adjusted for covariates (e.g. individual differences) before testing treatment differences.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models are able to analyze these experiments without the assumptions of homogeneity-of-regression slopes that is required by ANCOVA.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models can be used on data with many levels, although 2-level models are the most common and the rest of this article deals only with these.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The dependent variable must be examined at the lowest level of analysis.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] When there are multiple level 1 independent variables, the model can be expanded by substituting vectors and matrices in the equation.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] When the relationship between the response $Y_{ij}$ and predictor $X_{ij}$ can not be described by the linear relationship, then one can find some non linear functional relationship between the response and predictor, and extend the model to nonlinear mixed-effects model.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] For example, when the response $Y_{ij}$ is the cumulative infection trajectory of the i -th country, and $X_{ij}$ represents the j -th time points, then the ordered pair $(X_{ij},Y_{ij})$ for each country may show a shape similar to logistic function.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The dependent variables are the intercepts and the slopes for the independent variables at Level 1 in the groups of Level 2.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Before conducting a multilevel model analysis, a researcher must decide on several aspects, including which predictors are to be included in the analysis, if any.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Second, the researcher must decide whether parameter values (i.e., the elements that will be estimated) will be fixed or random.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Fixed parameters are composed of a constant over all the groups, whereas a random parameter has a different value for each of the groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Additionally, the researcher must decide whether to employ a maximum likelihood estimation or a restricted maximum likelihood estimation type.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] A random intercepts model is a model in which intercepts are allowed to vary, and therefore, the scores on the dependent variable for each individual observation are predicted by the intercept that varies across groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This model assumes that slopes are fixed (the same across different contexts).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In addition, this model provides information about intraclass correlations, which are helpful in determining whether multilevel models are required in the first place.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] A random slopes model is a model in which slopes are allowed to vary according to a correlation matrix, and therefore, the slopes are different across grouping variable such as time or individuals.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This model assumes that intercepts are fixed (the same across different contexts).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] A model that includes both random intercepts and random slopes is likely the most realistic type of model, although it is also the most complex.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In this model, both intercepts and slopes are allowed to vary across groups, meaning that they are different in different contexts.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In order to conduct a multilevel model analysis, one would start with fixed coefficients (slopes and intercepts).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] One aspect would be allowed to vary at a time (that is, would be changed), and compared with the previous model in order to assess better model fit.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] There are three different questions that a researcher would ask in assessing a model.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Third, what contribution do individual predictors make to the model?
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In order to assess models, different model fit statistics would be examined.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] One such statistic is the chi-square likelihood-ratio test, which assesses the difference between models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The likelihood-ratio test can be employed for model building in general, for examining what happens when effects in a model are allowed to vary, and when testing a dummy-coded categorical variable as a single effect.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, the test can only be used when models are nested (meaning that a more complex model includes all of the effects of a simpler model).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] When testing non-nested models, comparisons between models can be made using the Akaike information criterion (AIC) or the Bayesian information criterion (BIC), among others.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models have the same assumptions as other major general linear models (e.g., ANOVA, regression), but some of the assumptions are modified for the hierarchical nature of the design (i.e., nested data).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The assumption of linearity states that there is a rectilinear (straight-line, as opposed to non-linear or U-shaped) relationship between variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, the model can be extended to nonlinear relationships.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Particularly, when the mean part of the level 1 regression equation is replaced with a non-linear parametric function, then such a model framework is widely called the nonlinear mixed-effects model.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The assumption of normality states that the error terms at every level of the model are normally distributed.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, most statistical software allows one to specify different distributions for the variance terms, such as a Poisson, binomial, logistic.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The multilevel modelling approach can be used for all forms of Generalized Linear models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The assumption of homoscedasticity, also known as homogeneity of variance, assumes equality of population variances.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, different variance-correlation matrix can be specified to account for this, and the heterogeneity of variance can itself be modeled.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Independence is an assumption of general linear models, which states that cases are random samples from the population and that scores on the dependent variable are independent of each other.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The regressors must not correlate with the random effects, $u_{0j}$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This assumption is testable but often ignored, rendering the estimator inconsistent.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] If this assumption is violated, the random-effect must be modeled explicitly in the fixed part of the model, either by using dummy variables or including cluster means of all $X_{ij}$ regressors.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This assumption is probably the most important assumption the estimator makes, but one that is misunderstood by most applied researchers using these types of models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The type of statistical tests that are employed in multilevel models depend on whether one is examining fixed effects or variance components.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] When examining fixed effects, the tests are compared with the standard error of the fixed effect, which results in a Z-test.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] When computing a t-test, it is important to keep in mind the degrees of freedom, which will depend on the level of the predictor (e.g., level 1 predictor or level 2 predictor).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] For a level 1 predictor, the degrees of freedom are based on the number of level 1 predictors, the number of groups and the number of individual observations.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] For a level 2 predictor, the degrees of freedom are based on the number of level 2 predictors and the number of groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Statistical power for multilevel models differs depending on whether it is level 1 or level 2 effects that are being examined.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Power for level 1 effects is dependent upon the number of individual observations, whereas the power for level 2 effects is dependent upon the number of groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] To conduct research with sufficient power, large sample sizes are required in multilevel models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, the number of individual observations in groups is not as important as the number of groups in a study.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The concept of level is the keystone of this approach.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The researcher must establish for each variable the level at which it was measured.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In this example "test score" might be measured at pupil level, "teacher experience" at class level, "school funding" at school level, and "urban" at district level.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] As a simple example, consider a basic linear regression model that predicts income as a function of age, class, gender and race.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] It might then be observed that income levels also vary depending on the city and state of residence.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] A simple way to incorporate this into the regression model would be to add an additional independent categorical variable to account for the location (i.e. a set of additional binary predictors and associated regression coefficients, one per location).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This would have the effect of shifting the mean income up or down—but it would still assume, for example, that the effect of race and gender on income is the same everywhere.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In reality, this is unlikely to be the case—different local laws, different retirement policies, differences in level of racial prejudice, etc. are likely to cause all of the predictors to have different sorts of effects in different locales.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In other words, a simple linear regression model might, for example, predict that a given randomly sampled person in Seattle would have an average yearly income $10,000 higher than a similar person in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, it would also predict, for example, that a white person might have an average income $7,000 above a black person, and a 65-year-old might have an income $3,000 below a 45-year-old, in both cases regardless of location.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] A multilevel model, however, would allow for different regression coefficients for each predictor in each location.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Essentially, it would assume that people in a given location have correlated incomes generated by a single set of regression coefficients, whereas people in another location have incomes generated by a different set of coefficients.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Meanwhile, the coefficients themselves are assumed to be correlated and generated from a single set of hyperparameters.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Additional levels are possible: For example, people might be grouped by cities, and the city-level regression coefficients grouped by state, and the state-level coefficients generated from a single hyper-hyperparameter.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models are a subclass of hierarchical Bayesian models, which are general models with multiple levels of random variables and arbitrary relationships among the different variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel analysis has been extended to include multilevel structural equation modeling, multilevel latent class modeling, and other more general models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models have been used in education research or geographical research, to estimate separately the variance between pupils within the same school, and the variance between schools.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In psychological applications, the multiple levels are items in an instrument, individuals, and families.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In sociological applications, multilevel models are used to examine individuals embedded within regions or countries.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] In organizational psychology research, data from individuals must often be nested within teams or other functional units.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] They are often used in ecological research as well under the more general term mixed models.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Different covariables may be relevant on different levels.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] They can be used for longitudinal studies, as with growth studies, to separate changes within one individual and differences between individuals.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Cross-level interactions may also be of substantive interest; for example, when a slope is allowed to vary randomly, a level-2 predictor may be included in the slope formula for the level-1 covariate.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] For example, one may estimate the interaction of race and neighborhood to obtain an estimate of the interaction between an individual's characteristics and the social context.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] There are several alternative ways of analyzing hierarchical data, although most of them have some problems.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] First, traditional statistical techniques can be used.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] One could disaggregate higher-order variables to the individual level, and thus conduct an analysis on this individual level (for example, assign class variables to the individual level).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The problem with this approach is that it would violate the assumption of independence, and thus could bias the results.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Another way to analyze the data using traditional statistical approaches is to aggregate individual level variables to higher-order variables and then to conduct an analysis on this higher level.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The problem with this approach is that it discards all within-group information (because it takes the average of the individual level variables).
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] As much as 80–90% of the variance could be wasted, and the relationship between aggregated variables is inflated, and thus distorted.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This is known as ecological fallacy, and statistically, this type of analysis results in decreased power in addition to the loss of information.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Another way to analyze hierarchical data would be through a random-coefficients model.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This model assumes that each group has a different regression model—with its own intercept and slope.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Because groups are sampled, the model assumes that the intercepts and slopes are also randomly sampled from a population of group intercepts and slopes.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This allows for an analysis in which one can assume that slopes are fixed but intercepts are allowed to vary.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However this presents a problem, as individual components are independent but group components are independent between groups, but dependent within groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] This also allows for an analysis in which the slopes are random; however, the correlations of the error terms (disturbances) are dependent on the values of the individual-level variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Thus, the problem with using a random-coefficients model in order to analyze hierarchical data is that it is still not possible to incorporate higher order variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel models have two error terms, which are also known as disturbances.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] The individual components are all independent, but there are also group components, which are independent between groups but correlated within groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] However, variance components can differ, as some groups are more homogeneous than others.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Multilevel modeling is frequently used in diverse applications and it can be formulated by the Bayesian framework.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Particularly, Bayesian nonlinear mixed-effects models have recently received significant attention.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Parameters involved in the model are written in Greek letters. $f(t;\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{K})$ is a known function parameterized by the K -dimensional vector $(\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{K})$ .
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] If ***Stage 3: Prior*** is not considered, then the model reduces to a frequentist nonlinear mixed-effect model.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Standard research cycle involves literature review, defining a problem and specifying the research question and hypothesis.
[src:hierarchical-models/multilevel-model] Bayesian-specific workflow comprises three sub-steps: (b)–(i) formalizing prior distributions based on background knowledge and prior elicitation; (b)–(ii) determining the likelihood function based on a nonlinear function f ; and (b)–(iii) making a posterior inference.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] In econometrics, a **random effects model**, also called a **variance components model**, is a statistical model where the model effects are random variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] It is a kind of hierarchical linear model, which assumes that the data being analysed are drawn from a hierarchy of different populations whose differences relate to that hierarchy.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] A random effects model is a special case of a mixed model.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Contrast this to the biostatistics definitions, as biostatisticians use "fixed" and "random" effects to respectively refer to the population-average and subject-specific effects (and where the latter are generally assumed to be unknown, latent variables).
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Random effect models assist in controlling for unobserved heterogeneity when the heterogeneity is constant over time and not correlated with independent variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Two common assumptions can be made about the individual specific effect: the random effects assumption and the fixed effects assumption.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The random effects assumption is that the individual unobserved heterogeneity is uncorrelated with the independent variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The fixed effect assumption is that the individual specific effect can be correlated with the independent variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] If the random effects assumption holds, the random effects estimator is more efficient than the fixed effects model.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Suppose m large elementary schools are chosen randomly from among thousands in a large country.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Suppose also that n pupils of the same age are chosen randomly at each selected school.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Their scores on a standard aptitude test are ascertained.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Let $Y_{ij}$ be the score of the j -th pupil at the i -th school.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] where $\mu$ is the average test score for the entire population.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] In this model $U_{i}$ is the school-specific **random effect**: it measures the difference between the average score at school i and the average score in the entire country.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The term $W_{ij}$ is the individual-specific random effect, i.e., it's the deviation of the j -th pupil's score from the average for the i -th school.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The model can be augmented by including additional explanatory variables, which would capture differences in scores among different groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] where $\mathrm {Sex} _{ij}$ is a binary dummy variable and $\mathrm {ParentsEduc} _{ij}$ records, say, the average education level of a child's parents.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] This is a mixed model, not a purely random effects model, as it introduces fixed-effects terms for Sex and Parents' Education.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The variance of $Y_{ij}$ is the sum of the variances $\tau ^{2}$ and $\sigma ^{2}$ of $U_{i}$ and $W_{ij}$ respectively.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] be the average, not of all scores at the i -th school, but of those at the i -th school that are included in the random sample.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] be respectively the sum of squares due to differences *within* groups and the sum of squares due to difference *between* groups.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] These "expected mean squares" can be used as the basis for estimation of the "variance components" $\sigma ^{2}$ and *$\tau ^{2}$*.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] The $\sigma ^{2}$ parameter is also called the intraclass correlation coefficient.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] For random effects models the marginal likelihoods are important.
[src:hierarchical-models/random-effects-model] Random effects models used in practice include the Bühlmann model of insurance contracts and the Fay-Herriot model used for small area estimation.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In statistics, **shrinkage** is the reduction in the effects of sampling variation.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In regression analysis, a fitted relationship appears to perform less well on a new data set than on the data set used for fitting.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In particular the value of the coefficient of determination 'shrinks'.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] A **shrinkage estimator** is an estimator that, either explicitly or implicitly, incorporates the effects of shrinkage.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In loose terms this means that a naive or raw estimate is improved by combining it with other information.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] The term relates to the notion that the improved estimate is made closer to the value supplied by the 'other information' than the raw estimate.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In this sense, shrinkage is used to regularize ill-posed inference problems.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Shrinkage is implicit in Bayesian inference and penalized likelihood inference, and explicit in James–Stein-type inference.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In contrast, simple types of maximum-likelihood and least-squares estimation procedures do not include shrinkage effects, although they can be used within shrinkage estimation schemes.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Many standard estimators can be improved, in terms of mean squared error (MSE), by shrinking them towards zero (or any other finite constant value).
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] In other words, the improvement in the estimate from the corresponding reduction in the width of the confidence interval can outweigh the worsening of the estimate introduced by biasing the estimate towards zero (see bias-variance tradeoff).
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Assume that the expected value of the raw estimate is not zero and consider other estimators obtained by multiplying the raw estimate by a certain parameter.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] A value for this parameter can be specified so as to minimize the MSE of the new estimate.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] For this value of the parameter, the new estimate will have a smaller MSE than the raw one, and thus it has been improved.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] An effect here may be to convert an unbiased raw estimate to an improved biased one.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] An example arises in the estimation of the population variance by sample variance.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] For a sample size of *n*, the use of a divisor *n*−1 in the usual formula (Bessel's correction) gives an unbiased estimator, while other divisors have lower MSE, at the expense of bias.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] The use of shrinkage estimators in the context of regression analysis, where there may be a large number of explanatory variables, has been described by Copas.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Here the values of the estimated regression coefficients are shrunk towards zero with the effect of reducing the mean square error of predicted values from the model when applied to new data.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] A later paper by Copas applies shrinkage in a context where the problem is to predict a binary response on the basis of binary explanatory variables.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Hausser and Strimmer "develop a James-Stein-type shrinkage estimator, resulting in a procedure that is highly efficient statistically as well as computationally.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Despite its simplicity, it outperforms eight other entropy estimation procedures across a diverse range of sampling scenarios and data-generating models, even in cases of severe undersampling. ... method is fully analytic and hence computationally inexpensive.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] Moreover, procedure simultaneously provides estimates of the entropy and of the cell frequencies.
[src:hierarchical-models/shrinkage-estimator] The proposed shrinkage estimators of entropy and mutual information, as well as all other investigated entropy estimators, have been implemented in R (R Development Core Team, 2008).
